<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="50543" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="50543">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="50543">
This species was recorded from West Africa (from Guinea-Bissau to Nigeria) to Central (Democratic Republic of the Congo) and Eastern Africa. Especially because it was already known from the Cross River State in Nigeria (
<bibRefCitation author="Larsen, T. B." journalOrPublisher="Apollo Books, Stenstrup, Denmark" pageId="0" pageNumber="50543" refId="B5501287" refString="Larsen, T. B., 2005. Butterflies of West Africa. Apollo Books, Stenstrup, Denmark" title="Butterflies of West Africa" year="2005">Larsen 2005</bibRefCitation>
), its occurrence in Cameroon could be expected. We collected four specimens, each in a different disturbed lowland forest (from 20 to 660 m a.s.l.), therefore the species seems to be widespread, but locally scarce in Cameroon. This fully corresponds with T. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Larsen’s">Larsen's</normalizedToken>
experience with this species in Nigeria (
<bibRefCitation author="Larsen, T. B." journalOrPublisher="Apollo Books, Stenstrup, Denmark" pageId="0" pageNumber="50543" refId="B5501287" refString="Larsen, T. B., 2005. Butterflies of West Africa. Apollo Books, Stenstrup, Denmark" title="Butterflies of West Africa" year="2005">Larsen 2005</bibRefCitation>
) (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 33" captionStartId="F5502897" captionText="Figure 33. Eurema floricola leonis (Butler, 1886). A. dorsal view; B. ventral view. The scale bar represents 1 cm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e50543.figure33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/375385" pageId="0" pageNumber="50543">33</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
